Required Tech Stack
 
This project must use only the following stack:
 
- Frontend: exactly one HTML file, CSS, and vanilla JavaScript, with Bootstrap allowed for styling only
- Backend: ASP.NET Core Web API (`dotnet`), C#
- Database: MySQL
 
# Frontend Constraints
 
- Use plain `.html`, `.css`, and `.js` files
- Maintain a single HTML entry file for the frontend (no multi-page HTML architecture)
- Drive UI/content/state transitions through JavaScript DOM updates
- Do not rely on server-rendered page transitions or additional HTML files for feature flows
- Bootstrap is allowed strictly for styling/layout via CSS classes and optional Bootstrap JS utilities
- Do not introduce frontend frameworks or component libraries beyond Bootstrap styling (e.g., React, Vue, Angular, Svelte, Next.js, Nuxt)
- Do not introduce frontend package managers or bundlers for app code (e.g., npm-based SPA tooling, Vite, Webpack, Parcel)
- Prefer browser-native APIs (`fetch`, `addEventListener`, `classList`, `localStorage`) and progressive enhancement patterns
 
# Backend Constraints
 
- Use ASP.NET Core Web API for all server endpoints
- Keep backend logic in C# project(s) managed by `dotnet`
- Do not use ORMs (e.g., Entity Framework, Dapper-style ORM mapping abstractions)
- Access MySQL with direct SQL queries/commands you write explicitly
- Keep SQL visible and reviewable in the backend codebase (no hidden query generation layers)
- Do not introduce alternative backend runtimes/frameworks (e.g., Node/Express, Django, Rails, Spring)
 
# Database Constraints
 
- Use MySQL as the primary relational database
- Use MySQL-compatible schema, SQL dialect, and connection configuration
- Do not switch to other primary databases (e.g., PostgreSQL, SQL Server, MongoDB) unless explicitly requested
 
# Dependency Policy
 
- No new packages/frameworks that conflict with this stack policy
- If a proposed change requires tooling outside this stack, stop and ask for explicit approval first
 
# Quick Examples
 
```text
Allowed:
- single `index.html` + styles.css + app.js
- Bootstrap CSS classes for layout/components and optional Bootstrap JS utilities
- JavaScript-driven view updates (show/hide sections, render lists/forms, update content dynamically)
- ASP.NET Core controllers/minimal APIs in C#
- MySQL tables and hand-written SQL queries in backend data access code
 
Not allowed:
- Multiple HTML pages for app feature flows
- Feature behavior implemented by manual HTML page swapping instead of JS-driven rendering
- Entity Framework or other ORM-based data access
- Auto-generated/implicit query layers instead of explicit SQL
- React + Vite frontend
- Express.js backend
- PostgreSQL migration
